{"parse":{"title":"Nimrud lens","pageid":12314286,"revid":846614852,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\">The Nimrud Lens</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Nimrud lens British Museum.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg/220px-Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"196\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg/330px-Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg/440px-Nimrud_lens_British_Museum.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1040\" data-file-height=\"926\" /></a><div>The lens on display in the British Museum</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Material</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Quartz\" title=\"Quartz\">Rock crystal</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Size</th><td>\nDiameter: 38&#160;mm (1.5&#160;in)<br />Thickness: 23&#160;mm (0.9&#160;in)<sup id=\"cite_ref-layard_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-layard-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Brewster_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Brewster-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Created</th><td>\n750\u2013710&#160;BC</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Period/culture</th><td>\nNeo-Assyrian</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Discovered</th><td>\n1850<br />Assyrian palace of Nimrud</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Discovered by</th><td>\nAusten Henry Layard</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Place</th><td>\nNorth West Palace, Room AB</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Present location</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>, London</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Identification</th><td>\n<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/search_object_details.aspx?objectid=369215&amp;partid=1\">90959 </a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <b>Nimrud lens</b>, also called <b>Layard lens</b>, is a 3000-year-old piece of <a href=\"/wiki/Rock_crystal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Rock crystal\">rock crystal</a>, which was unearthed in 1850 by <a href=\"/wiki/Austen_Henry_Layard\" title=\"Austen Henry Layard\">Austen Henry Layard</a> at the <a href=\"/wiki/Assyria\" title=\"Assyria\">Assyrian</a> palace of <a href=\"/wiki/Nimrud\" title=\"Nimrud\">Nimrud</a>, in modern-day <a href=\"/wiki/Iraq\" title=\"Iraq\">Iraq</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-bm_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bm-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> It may have been used as a <a href=\"/wiki/Magnifying_glass\" title=\"Magnifying glass\">magnifying glass</a>, or as a <a href=\"/wiki/Burning-glass\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Burning-glass\">burning-glass</a> to start fires by concentrating sunlight, or it may have been a piece of decorative inlay.<sup id=\"cite_ref-bm_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bm-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Interpretation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Interpretation</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Bibliography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bibliography</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nimrud_lens&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Lens_(optics)\" title=\"Lens (optics)\">lens</a> is slightly oval and was roughly <a href=\"/wiki/Grinding_(abrasive_cutting)\" title=\"Grinding (abrasive cutting)\">ground</a>, perhaps on a <a href=\"/wiki/Lapidary\" title=\"Lapidary\">lapidary</a> wheel.<sup id=\"cite_ref-layard_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-layard-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It has a <a href=\"/wiki/Focus_(optics)\" title=\"Focus (optics)\">focal point</a> about 11 centimetres (4.5&#160;in) from the flat side and a <a href=\"/wiki/Focal_length\" title=\"Focal length\">focal length</a> of about 12&#160;cm.<sup id=\"cite_ref-layard_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-layard-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Brewster_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Brewster-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-bm_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bm-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> This would make it equivalent to a 3\u00d7 magnifying glass. The surface of the lens has twelve cavities that were opened during grinding, which would have contained <a href=\"/wiki/Naphtha\" title=\"Naphtha\">naphtha</a> or some other fluid trapped in the raw crystal. The lens is said to be able to focus sunlight although the focus is far from perfect. Because the lens is made from natural rock crystal the material of the lens has not deteriorated significantly over time.<sup id=\"cite_ref-layard_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-layard-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Nimrud lens is on display in the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Interpretation\">Interpretation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nimrud_lens&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Interpretation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The function of the lens is not clear, with some authors suggesting that it was used as an optical lens and others suggesting a decorative function.\n</p><p>Assyrian craftsmen made intricate engravings and could have used a magnifying lens in their work.<sup id=\"cite_ref-BBC_News_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BBC_News-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The discoverer of the lens noted that he had found very small inscriptions on Assyrian artefacts which he suspected had been achieved with the aid of a lens.<sup id=\"cite_ref-layard_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-layard-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Italian scientist <a href=\"/wiki/Giovanni_Pettinato\" title=\"Giovanni Pettinato\">Giovanni Pettinato</a> of the University of Rome has proposed that the lens was used by the <a href=\"/wiki/Assyrian_people\" title=\"Assyrian people\">ancient Assyrians</a> as part of a <a href=\"/wiki/Optical_telescope\" title=\"Optical telescope\">telescope</a> and that this explains their knowledge of <a href=\"/wiki/Astronomy\" title=\"Astronomy\">astronomy</a> (see <a href=\"/wiki/Babylonian_astronomy\" title=\"Babylonian astronomy\">Babylonian astronomy</a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-BBC_News_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BBC_News-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Experts on Assyrian <a href=\"/wiki/Archaeology\" title=\"Archaeology\">archaeology</a> are unconvinced, doubting that the optical quality of the lens is sufficient to be of much use. The ancient Assyrians saw the planet <a href=\"/wiki/Saturn\" title=\"Saturn\">Saturn</a> as a god surrounded by a ring of serpents, which Pettinato suggests was their interpretation of Saturn's rings as seen through a telescope.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Other experts say that serpents occur frequently in Assyrian mythology and note that there is no mention of a telescope in any of the many surviving Assyrian astronomical writings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-BBC_News_5-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BBC_News-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>According to his book, Layard found the lens buried beneath other pieces of glass which looked like the enamel of an object, perhaps made of wood or ivory, which had disintegrated.<sup id=\"cite_ref-bm_3-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bm-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The British Museum curator's notes propose that the lens could have been used \"as a piece of inlay, perhaps for furniture\" and that there is no evidence that the Assyrians used lenses for their optical qualities, e.g. for magnification, telescopy or for starting fire.<sup id=\"cite_ref-bm_3-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-bm-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nimrud_lens&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Visby_lenses\" title=\"Visby lenses\">Visby lenses</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nimrud_lens&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-layard-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-layard_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-layard_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-layard_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-layard_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-layard_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Layard, Austen Henry (1853). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/?id=1KITAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA674&amp;dq=british+museum+lens+layard#v=onepage&amp;q=lens&amp;f=false\"><i>Discoveries in the ruins of Nineveh and Babylon: with travels in Armenia</i></a>. G.P. Putnam and Co. pp.&#160;197\u20138,674.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Discoveries+in+the+ruins+of+Nineveh+and+Babylon%3A+with+travels+in+Armenia&amp;rft.pages=197-8%2C674&amp;rft.pub=G.P.+Putnam+and+Co&amp;rft.date=1853&amp;rft.aulast=Layard&amp;rft.aufirst=Austen+Henry&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3D1KITAAAAYAAJ%26pg%3DPA674%26dq%3Dbritish%2Bmuseum%2Blens%2Blayard%23v%3Donepage%26q%3Dlens%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANimrud+lens\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Brewster-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Brewster_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Brewster_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">D. Brewster (1852). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/?id=bHwEAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=RA1-PA355&amp;dq=niniveh+lens\">\"On an account of a rock-crystal lens and decomposed glass found in Niniveh\"</a>. <i>Die Fortschritte der Physik</i> (in German). Deutsche Physikalische Gesellschaft.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Die+Fortschritte+der+Physik&amp;rft.atitle=On+an+account+of+a+rock-crystal+lens+and+decomposed+glass+found+in+Niniveh&amp;rft.date=1852&amp;rft.au=D.+Brewster&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DbHwEAAAAYAAJ%26pg%3DRA1-PA355%26dq%3Dniniveh%2Blens&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANimrud+lens\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-bm-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-bm_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-bm_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-bm_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-bm_3-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-bm_3-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/search_object_details.aspx?objectid=369215&amp;partid=1\">\"The Nimrud lens / the Layard lens\"</a>. <i>Collection database</i>. The British Museum<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">Oct 21,</span> 2012</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Collection+database&amp;rft.atitle=The+Nimrud+lens+%2F+the+Layard+lens&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britishmuseum.org%2Fresearch%2Fsearch_the_collection_database%2Fsearch_object_details.aspx%3Fobjectid%3D369215%26partid%3D1&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANimrud+lens\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Villiers, Geoffrey de; Pike, E. Roy (2016-10-16). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.it/books?id=mCqLDQAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT35&amp;lpg=PT35&amp;dq=layard+lens+1850&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=jZdkfLIvL6&amp;sig=a4v6JQNVJoOczRqiED78mlhfcNM&amp;hl=it&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjJvZatsYrRAhUHCBoKHUdDA9g4ChDoAQhGMAo#v=onepage&amp;q=layard%20lens%201850&amp;f=false\"><i>The Limits of Resolution</i></a>. CRC Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781315350806\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781315350806\">9781315350806</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Limits+of+Resolution&amp;rft.pub=CRC+Press&amp;rft.date=2016-10-16&amp;rft.isbn=9781315350806&amp;rft.aulast=Villiers&amp;rft.aufirst=Geoffrey+de&amp;rft.au=Pike%2C+E.+Roy&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.it%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DmCqLDQAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT35%26lpg%3DPT35%26dq%3Dlayard%2Blens%2B1850%26source%3Dbl%26ots%3DjZdkfLIvL6%26sig%3Da4v6JQNVJoOczRqiED78mlhfcNM%26hl%3Dit%26sa%3DX%26ved%3D0ahUKEwjJvZatsYrRAhUHCBoKHUdDA9g4ChDoAQhGMAo%23v%3Donepage%26q%3Dlayard%2520lens%25201850%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANimrud+lens\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-BBC_News-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-BBC_News_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-BBC_News_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-BBC_News_5-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Whitehouse, David (July 1, 1999). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/380186.stm\">\"World's oldest telescope?\"</a>. <i>BBC News</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 10,</span> 2008</span>. <q>If one Italian scientist is correct then the telescope was not invented sometime in the 16th century by Dutch spectacle makers, but by ancient Assyrian astronomers nearly three thousand years earlier. According to Professor Giovanni Pettinato of the University of Rome, a rock crystal lens, currently on show in the British museum, could rewrite the history of science. He believes that it could explain why the ancient Assyrians knew so much about astronomy.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=BBC+News&amp;rft.atitle=World%27s+oldest+telescope%3F&amp;rft.date=1999-07-01&amp;rft.aulast=Whitehouse&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnews.bbc.co.uk%2F1%2Fhi%2Fsci%2Ftech%2F380186.stm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANimrud+lens\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20070929091502/http://www.exn.ca/Stories/1999/06/29/63.asp\">\"World's oldest telescope?\"</a>. <i>EXN Science Wire</i>. June 29, 1999. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.exn.ca/Stories/1999/06/29/63.asp\">the original</a> on Sep 29, 2007<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2008-05-10</span></span>. <q>Pettinato believes the lens was used by Assyrian astronomers as a telescope more than three thousand years ago. They saw more in the night sky than was possible with the naked eye alone. For example, the Assyrians saw the planet Saturn as a god surrounded by a ring of serpents. Pettinato says that would be a logical assumption to make if they saw Saturn's rings through a primitive telescope.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=EXN+Science+Wire&amp;rft.atitle=World%27s+oldest+telescope%3F&amp;rft.date=1999-06-29&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.exn.ca%2FStories%2F1999%2F06%2F29%2F63.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANimrud+lens\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bibliography\">Bibliography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nimrud_lens&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Bibliography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>A. H. Layard, <i>Discoveries in the Ruins of Nineveh and Babylon</i> (London, 1853), p.&#160;197\u201398.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nimrud_lens&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.lcas-astronomy.org/articles/display.php?filename=oldest_optical_device_-_the_nimrud_lens&amp;category=general\">Oldest Optical Device? The Nimrud Lens</a></li></ul>\n<dl><dd><i>This article is about an item held in the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>. The object reference is <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/search_object_details.aspx?objectid=369215&amp;partid=1\">ME 90959</a>.</i></dd></dl>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span id=\"coordinates\"><a href=\"/wiki/Geographic_coordinate_system\" title=\"Geographic coordinate system\">Coordinates</a>: <span class=\"plainlinks nourlexpansion\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Nimrud_lens&amp;params=36.0992_N_43.3275_E_source:wikidata\"><span class=\"geo-nondefault\"><span class=\"geo-dms\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\"><span class=\"latitude\">36\u00b005\u203257\u2033N</span> <span class=\"longitude\">43\u00b019\u203239\u2033E</span></span></span><span class=\"geo-multi-punct\">&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;</span><span class=\"geo-default\"><span class=\"geo-dec\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\">36.0992\u00b0N 43.3275\u00b0E</span><span style=\"display:none\">&#xfeff; / <span class=\"geo\">36.0992; 43.3275</span></span></span></a></span></span></span>\n</p>\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2226\nCached time: 20180917165925\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.212 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.258 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 793/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 19642/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 1194/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 8/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 98